  <span id="freeText6105202772095220462" style="display:none">Letâ€™s play the â€œwho wants to be horrifiedâ€ game. Complications made it hard to sleep. Not because of gore necessarily but because it made clear to me that doctors are just people who were given a scalpel. Yes, they have a ton of education but at some point, they must get experience.<br /><br />In one section Gawande discusses a procedure in which he must put in a central line which goes into a major vein in your chest which can technically kill you. All he tells the patient is that he must put in a central line, not that it is dangerous or that it is his first time doing this procedure. I completely understand why he didnâ€™t tell the patient, but that doesnâ€™t make it any less terrifying. I have thought about how doctors have to start at some point, but it was never so clear to me that there is a first patient for every procedure for every doctor. For every surgeon, there will be the first surgery. There is a first time for cutting into the flesh of a still-living person.<br /><br />It was published in 2002 so Iâ€™m sure some things have changed, but itâ€™s still current enough about how the training takes place.<br /><br />Itâ€™s an important realization of how much control doctors have over our bodies and how little they have over everything else in the hospital. They donâ€™t get to choose...<br />For the full review please visit <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.literarydragonreviews.website/2019/09/22/complications-a-surgeons-notes-on-an-imperfect-science-by-atul-gawande/">https://www.literarydragonreviews.web...</a></span>
